               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18400302-979-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-979-18400302 t18400302-979-offence-1 t18400302-979-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>979. <persName id="def1-979-18400302" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-979-18400302" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-979-18400302" type="age" value="17"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-979-18400302" type="surname" value="ELLIOTT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-979-18400302" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ROBERT ELLIOTT</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18400302-979-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18400302-979-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18400302-979-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18400302-cd-173" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18400302-979-offence-1 t18400302-cd-173"></join>28th of February</rs>, 1 spoon, value 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18400302-name-1016" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1016" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1016" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1016" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18400302-979-offence-1 t18400302-name-1016"></join>Benjamin Smith</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400302-name-1017" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1017" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1017" type="surname" value="DOWSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1017" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN DOWSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a pawnbroker, and live in Skilton's-lane, Green<lb></lb>wich. On Friday, the 28th of February, in the evening, the prisoner came into my shop with a silver tea-spoon—he laid it on the counter—I was busy at the time, having no one else in the shop—I suspected it was stolen—I took it up, looked at it, and was not able to make out the initials—the prisoner said, "It is old silver"—I said, "I suppose you want to sell it then?"—he said "Yes"—I asked his name—he said, "Smith, my mother sent me with the spoon, and the name of Smith is on it"—I put it on one side a little time, went to the door, and called an officer—I then told the prisoner I thought he had either found or stolen the spoon—he said he had found it on Deptford-bridge—I said the spoon appeared to have been used where there was a family—it seemed to have been bit—I asked him on which side the initials of "Smith" were—he said, "On the back"—it was "W. S." on it, which I believe are the initials of the person—I said it was Mr. Benjamin Smith's, the proprietor of the wharf—he said it was not, and I gave him in charge—he said afterwards his name was Robert Elliott.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400302-name-1018" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1018" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1018" type="surname" value="HARRISS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1018" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE HARRISS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable R</hi> 158.) I was called into the shop—the prisoner was having some conversation with Mr. Dowson—I asked him his name, and he said, "Smith"—that his mother's name was Smith—I asked where he worked—he said, for Mr. Smith, at Deptford-bridge—I said, "How do you account for the spoon?"—he said he had found it on Deptford-bridge—I took him into custody, and received the spoon from Mr. Dowson.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184003020192"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400302-name-1019" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1019" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1019" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1019" type="given" value="EMMA"></interp>EMMA WHITE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am servant to Mr. Benjamin Smith, a stone-mason, of Albion wharf. I know the prisoner—he is employed by my master to do any thing about the wharf—he comes into the kitchen sometimes—I had left a spoon on a mangle in the kitchen—this is Mr. Smith's spoon—I cannot swear he took it off the mangle—I left it there, and lost it—he was in and out of the kitchen on the day in question.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I found the spoon outside the house-door, but I did not think it belonged to the house—I found a gold brooch there be<lb></lb>fore, and gave that to my mistress.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400302-name-1020" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1020" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1020" type="surname" value="DOWSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1020" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN DOWSON</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> The prisoner's father has been employed by the prosecutor for a length of time, and has borne an irreproachable character—the prisoner was in his employ three months, and he knew no<lb></lb>thing wrong of him—what he states about the brooch is a fact—he did find it on the premises, and gave it to his mistress—the prosecutor told me that the spoon might have been outside near his house, as he has a large family and the children might have thrown it there—the initials on the spoon are "M. H."—it was the property of his wife before their marriage, and they have others to correspond with it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400302-name-1021" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1021" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1021" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400302-name-1021" type="given" value="EMMA"></interp>EMMA WHITE</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> The children might have carried the spoon outside and dropped it—the prisoner has seen me with these spoons—they were kept in the kitchen.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18400302-979-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18400302-979-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18400302-979-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="withRecommendation"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GUILTY</hi>. Aged 17.—<hi rend="italic">Recommended to mercy.</hi>
                  </rs>—
<rs id="t18400302-979-punishment-189" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18400302-979-punishment-189" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
